I don't care if Monday's blue,
Tuesday's great and Wednesday too--
Thursday I don't care about you,
It's Friday I'm in love.

Monday you can fall apart,
Tuesday, Wednesday break my heart,
Thursday doesn't even start,
It's Friday I'm in love.

Saturday waits,
Sunday always comes too late,
Friday never hesitates.

Nothing of interest happened today. This morning I shopped; this afternoon I worked.
Only--my friend stopped by to pick up his paycheck. I was inordinately happy to see him. [He is a nice man--very reliable--he's in a rock band, and he goes to Med. school...] 
Oh, and, there are only two days until I leave for Italy. Yay!

<center>[--too much is not enough,
nobody said this stuff makes any sense,
we're hooked again.
The point of no return,
see how the buildings burn
light up the night,
such a pretty sight--]</center>
These past few days have been so crazy. I've hardly been at my house at all-- staying out every night and working at Rising High every day. I haven't had any sleep and right now I'm finishing off the last of a nicotine buzz.

Rising High was all topsy-turvy today. Ernest didn't show up for work, so I was assigned cafe duty. I got to make sandwiches and wash dishes and wrap pickles in sheets of wax paper. You can't imagine. Also, I lost, like, 2000 brain cells bleaching the cutting boards. Still, I finally got my valentine.
"The pure present is an ungraspable advance of the past devouring the future. In truth, all sensation is already memory."

Maybe I don't love anyone. Maybe no one loves me. Maybe I'll just sit here smoking cigarette after cigarette until I finish another pack. Maybe none of this matters. Maybe none of this ever mattered. Maybe I wanted it too much. Maybe I didn't want it enough. Maybe this is how it's supposed to end.

I have a bruise on my hip and a bitemark on my left shoulder. My new Hollister shirt is marked with a grass stain and my fingers smell like tobacco. The past few nights I haven't been sleeping. Still, I'm happier than I have been in months.

So, prom is tomorrow and I'm going. Who would have thought? I bought my dress yesterday--it's really pretty. This morning, before work, I'm going shoe-shopping. I've decided that, since I don't have my own, I'll steal other people's dates to dance with.

<center>[And so never ask why,
don't say anything nice,
and don't talk 
if we meet on the field.
I just want you to know,
that I let it all go,
even if you never did.]</center>

I haven't posted in, like, for-fucking-ever! So much has changed, even in the past twenty-four hours. Just this morning I chipped one of my front teeth so that it has a jagged edge. Oh God! Now I'm reading Baudelaire and trying to find a submission for lit. mag. "I long for darkness, silence, nothing there..."
THE FIRST OF THE LINE IS TIED TO A TREE AND THE LAST IS BEING EATEN BY THE ANTS.

Darlings-- I have a new e-mail address to give you all and I promise that this one is permanent. Because I switched ISPs, I had to set-up a new account. Just forget the two most recent domain names, sc.rr.com and hellokitty.com, and remember the newest, bellsouth.net. Really, I do apologize if this adjustment poses any serious inconvenience. much love, Jordan

Alecta--

"I took my morning walk, I took my evening walk, I ate something, I thought about something, I wrote something, I napped and dreamt something too, and with all that something, I still have nothing because so much of sum'things has always been and always will be you. I miss you."

I promise that your letter is on its way, darling.

Sweets to the sweet,

Jordan

[How long before I get in, before it starts, before I begin?] The beginning of this school year has been more difficult than others, it seems. Lately, I've degenerated into spending lunch inside the drama room, drinking Diet Coke, and humming The O.C. theme song. Still, Californ-i-a is hot--pirate patches are hot, fake eyelashes are hot, and Tab is hot.

[People say that you'll die faster than without water, but we know it's just a lie--scare you sons and scare your daughter--people say that your dreams are the only thing that save ya. Come on baby in our dreams, we can live our misbehaviour.] Earlier this afternoon I went to see Charlie and the Chocolate Factory with Alice and John. Really, though, I'm looking forward to The Corpse Bride in September.

My school schedule, as it stands: First Semester 1st block- Physics H 2nd block- Fine Art Appre. H 3rd block- Pre-Cal. H 4th block- Latin III H Second Semester 1st block- Latin IV H 2nd block- American Gov't./Econ. H 3rd block- AP Eng. Lit.

Hallelujah and pass the ammunition--I passed my Statistics exam! Much as I had predicted, 5-5-3. I can live with a 3, I can live with a 3, I can live with a 3...yes, I am satisfied. Now the saga is over, the chapter finished, the battle won. May I never again have to perform a chi-square test, Amen.

I've been back home three days and still everything is going well. I've had time to rest, to read, and to spend with Alice. Earlier today we drove around town and speculated on the secret life of a movie store clerk.

[--and we'll remember this when we are old and ancient, though the specifics might be vague, and I'll say your camisole was sprightly light magenta when in fact it was a nappy bluish grey.]

This afternoon while my parents were at mass I read Phaedrus. Lying back on the couch, I kept underlining passages and noting page numbers until Siegfried came and sat on my stomach so that I could hardly move for fear of being scratched. I enjoyed much of the book, still, and found the second character's arguments worth consideration. Mainly, the succession of speeches formed an extended discussion of rhetoric. All of the techniques were explained thoroughly and the distinction between "proper" and "improper" writing elaborated. I can't help wishing Ms. Dalton had suggested we read this before the AP exam, or even just gone over some of Plato's most relevant points...perhaps Ms. Paulovic would have. *sigh*
Friday was glorious--which is to say, I ♥ CARNIVALE.

This morning I took the AP English Language and Composition exam. Thanks to my uncommon luck, I was seated next to Richard Jordan. Several times, he began trying to talk with me, but I was like, "What the fuck!" and just laid my head down. [...he said, "I been around, I slept with who I like..."] Still, the multiple choice was a breeze and the only difficulty encountered was in writing three timed essays, one after another after another. Afterwards, I went out to lunch at Burger King with Jenny, Jessica, Kimberly, and Felicia. From there I came home to read The Arabian Nights. Now, I am thinking of studying Statistics for my second exam Wednesday.

That moment you've all been waiting for...
Jordan has again gone celluar. Besides her landphone, she can now be reached at (803) 317-4643.

[Everyone's a voyeurist and watching me watch them watch me right now...]
Eeek! I'm still working on Faulkner.

So, yeah, this morning I got in a wreck. Turning left onto S. Holly, I was hit on the driver's side by an oncoming pick-up truck. I climbed out only with a scratch, but the Buick was totaled. I wasn't wearing my seatbelt and was tossed across the passenger seat on impact.

It happened that I had pulled out too far past the stop sign, trying to see around the bushes, and, finding myself in a lane of traffic, tried to dart forward. Most clearly I remember thinking, as I watched the truck skidding towards me, "Oh my God, I'm going to be in so much trouble." How ironic, that at that exact second I was frightened, not of the threat to my personal safety, but of the inevitability of a revoked license!

Well, I got out and borrowed a neighbour's cell phone to call Alice and stood with another neighbour until she came. The police were called. Then I explained my mistake to the officer (who was terribly nice) and stood with Alice while towing was arranged and the accident report written up. The other driver was also understanding and even offered Alice and me some gum. When I began to apologize he only said, "All that matters is that neither of us was hurt."

By this time my mom had arrived. The legal situation was explained and the policeman recommended that instead of paying the $230.52 fine, I attend traffic court and try to avoid having the four points put on my license. The date is set for May 24th. I've cried a good deal and tried to argue my case to my parents, but from here on out it seems that I'll be walking. I can't believe this, really; it seems that instead I should be typing this into my dream journal under the category of "nightmare." Such a measure of freedom was lost; I'm furious with myself: how could I have made such a stupid mistake?

Today I

           spent the latter half of English class sunning myself on the baseball bleachers

           changed my lettucegirl lj background

           got a radical new hair cut

           finished watching Dimensia 13

           made a collage of Louise Brooks pictures around my bedroom mirror

Eight hours of sleep a night is one-third of our lives, almost twenty-five years. If our bodies are biologically-wired to cycle through one ninety-minute period after another, mightn't we at least enjoy the REM dreams? Couldn't we benefit from the nighttime fantasies that occupy our unconscious minds? 

[Playgirl, why are you sleeping in tomorrow's world--hey, Playgirl?]

I've decided to keep an online dream journal at http://www.livejournal.com/users/_1945_.

Someday I'd like read Venus in Furs...but thank God I finally finished Fountainhead! Now, as a reward, I've begun the novella, Morpho Eugenia. Tonight I may begin sketching out ideas for my Walpurgisnacht prom dress--which reminds me, tomorrow I must drive down Atuscadero (?) Road hand my Other Store guy an invitation--my Other Store guy deserves some recognition for rescuing me last Saturday from the demoniacal ice machine.

Prom is tonight and I am not going! Instead, I plan to read ghost stories and watch Arsenic and Old Lace with Alice. Also today I'm going thrift-store shopping, but I must remember to save enough money to buy a copy of Magnolia. [I know life is getting shorter, I can't bring myself to set the scene--]

I just got back last night from a three-day camping trip--never before have I so fully appreciated the beauty of a readily-available cd collection!

Claramonde--

I just remembered that I had forgotten to correct a blatant noun-pronoun agreement error in my "Come Fast Thy Prophecy" essay. Oh, c'est la vie. I'm sorry that I read your gracious reply too late, but you are more than welcome to use that one sentence in the literary magazine as a random picture caption...or maybe printed on the back inside cover?

Well, I must know, because of my own morbid fascination, do you have a "date" for prom? [Man, I feel like mould, it's prom night and I am lonely, low and behold! she's walking over to me, this must be fake, my lip starts to shake...] I almost wish that I could go myself, to show off a pretty new dress, but such a teenage fantasy, in the words of the late President Nixon, "is abhorrent to every instinct in my body."

I just read in the Free Times that Confederate Fagg is having another concert Sat. night at the Art Bar. I do so wish that I could go, but the timing is rather inconvenient, considering that the following day is Easter Sunday. ['I've got two tickets to Iron Maiden, Baby, come with me Friday, don't say maybe...'] 

Now, I shall get back to reading The Three Faces of Eve, a truly fascinating novel! Part of it, in fact, is rather creepy, as the patient finally recovers a repressed memory ("Mother...! Oh, Mother...! Don't make me...Don't...Don't...I can't do it! I can't!") of being made to touch her grandmother's dead face at a childhood funeral.

Bonne nuit,

Jordan

Even if it doesn't matter, I have been lying in bed all day with a terrible headache, alternately sleeping and scribbling away at two submissions for lit. mag. Now I have crawled over to my computer to begin typing:

                     It must first be explained that my fat cat Stanley has a nasty habit of eating fairies...

Jordan has lived through [sixteen] years of ignominy. During this time, she has achieved absolutely nothing, but has decided that she likes the name Lavinia and spends her time scheming to create infamy for herself. One day you may expect to see a duplicate model of her lithe form in a poorly-lit wax museum. Her main goal in life is receiving an excommunication from the pope himself. Currently, she attends D-- High School and collects money in a stash beneath her floorboards to fund a clandestine trip to California.

Wild horses couldn't drag me to the prom--never ever ever. Why would anyone want to spend $35 to go to a school-sponsored dance with two classes of obnoxious highschool students? Uckk. I passed the road test and now have a restricted licence! I am so excited! I feel so...mature. Wow! Once I got home from the DMV I drove all by my little lonesome over to Alice's to tell her the wonderful news. Everyone has been congratulating me and I can't wait to tell Mr. Mahelsky. Tomorrow, I plan to drive myself to the main library and browse through the reference section. Hopefully, too, Alice and I will be able to go to Target to buy some auto accoutrements (i.e. fuzzy dice, air freshener, Hello Kitty steering wheel cover). Life seems filled with so much...potential. I will never cry at night again--

(If you find that you have a little bit of free time, I recommend visiting a gorgeous Victorian Era website at missmary.com.)
